# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sigma-detection-rules
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] In statistics, **correlation** is a type of statistical relationship between two random variables or bivariate data.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] It usually refers to the extent to which a pair of quantities are linearly related.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] More generally, an arbitrary relationship between variables is called an **association**, meaning the degree to which the variability in one can be accounted for by the other.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The presence of a correlation is not sufficient to infer the presence of a causal relationship, and this is often stated as "correlation does not imply causation".
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Furthermore, the concept of correlation is not the same as dependence: if two variables are independent, then they are uncorrelated, but the opposite is not necessarily true – even if two variables are uncorrelated, they might be dependent on each other.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Correlations are useful because they can indicate a predictive relationship that can be exploited in practice.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] For example, an electrical utility may produce less power on a mild day based on the correlation between electricity demand and weather.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] In this example, there is a causal relationship, because extreme weather causes people to use more electricity for heating or cooling.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] There are several correlation coefficients that may be used to measure correlation, often denoted $\rho$ or r .
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The most common of these is the **Pearson correlation coefficient**, which is sensitive only to a linear relationship between two variables (which in turn may be present even when one variable is a nonlinear function of the other).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Other correlation coefficients, such as **Spearman's rank correlation coefficient**, have been developed to be more robust than Pearson's and to detect less structured relationships between variables.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The concept has been generalized to other forms of association between two variables, such as mutual information and distance covariance.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The most familiar measure of dependence between two quantities is the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient, most commonly called 'Pearson's correlation coefficient' or simply 'the correlation coefficient' (as it is the most common variant).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] It is obtained by taking the ratio of the covariance between two variables of a numerical dataset normalized to the square root of their variances.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Equivalently, Pearson's correlation coefficient can be calculated by dividing the covariance of the two variables by the product of their standard deviations.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Karl Pearson developed the coefficient from a similar idea by Francis Galton.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] A Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient attempts to establish a line of best fit through a dataset of two variables by essentially laying out the expected values and the resulting Pearson's correlation coefficient indicates how far away the actual dataset is from the expected values.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Depending on the sign of the Pearson's correlation coefficient, the result can be either a negative or positive correlation if there is any sort of relationship between the variables in the data set.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] where $\operatorname {E}$ is the expected value operator, $\operatorname {cov}$ means covariance, and $\operatorname {corr}$ is a widely used alternative notation for the correlation coefficient.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The Pearson correlation is defined only if both standard deviations are finite and positive.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] It is a corollary of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality that the absolute value of the Pearson correlation coefficient is not bigger than 1.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Therefore, the value of a correlation coefficient ranges between −1 and +1.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] As it approaches zero there is less of a relationship (closer to uncorrelated).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The closer the coefficient is to either −1 or 1, the stronger the correlation between the variables.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] If the variables are independent, Pearson's correlation coefficient is 0.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] However, because the correlation coefficient detects only linear dependencies between two variables, the converse is not necessarily true.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] A correlation coefficient of 0 does not imply that the variables are independent.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] For example, suppose the random variable X is symmetrically distributed about zero, and $Y=X^{2}$ .
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Then Y is completely determined by X , so that X and Y are perfectly dependent, but their correlation is zero; they are uncorrelated.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] However, in the special case when X and Y are jointly normal, uncorrelatedness is equivalent to independence.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Even though uncorrelated data does not necessarily imply independence, one can check if random variables are independent if their mutual information is 0.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Given a series of n measurements of the pair $(X_{i},Y_{i})$ indexed by $i=1,\ldots ,n$ , the *sample correlation coefficient* can be used to estimate the population Pearson correlation $\rho _{X,Y}$ between X and Y .
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] where ${\overline {x}}$ and ${\overline {y}}$ are the sample means of X and Y , and $s_{x}$ and $s_{y}$ are the corrected sample standard deviations of X and Y .
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] where $s'_{x}$ and $s'_{y}$ are the *uncorrected* sample standard deviations of X and Y .
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] If x and y are results of measurements that contain measurement error, the realistic limits on the correlation coefficient are not −1 to +1 but a smaller range.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] For the case of a linear model with a single independent variable, the coefficient of determination (R squared) is the square of $r_{xy}$ , Pearson's product-moment coefficient.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Consider the joint probability distribution of X and Y given in the table below.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Rank correlation coefficients, such as Spearman's rank correlation coefficient and Kendall's rank correlation coefficient (τ) measure the extent to which, as one variable increases, the other variable tends to increase, without requiring that increase to be represented by a linear relationship.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] If, as the one variable increases, the other *decreases*, the rank correlation coefficients will be negative.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] It is common to regard these rank correlation coefficients as alternatives to Pearson's coefficient, used either to reduce the amount of calculation or to make the coefficient less sensitive to non-normality in distributions.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] As we go from each pair to the next pair, x increases, and so does y .
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] This relationship is perfect, in the sense that an increase in x is *always* accompanied by an increase in y .
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] This means that we have a perfect rank correlation, and both Spearman's and Kendall's correlation coefficients are 1, whereas in this example Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient is 0.7544, indicating that the points are far from lying on a straight line.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] In the same way if y always *decreases* when x *increases*, the rank correlation coefficients will be −1, while the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient may or may not be close to −1, depending on how close the points are to a straight line.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Although in the extreme cases of perfect rank correlation the two coefficients are both equal (being both +1 or both −1), this is not generally the case, and so values of the two coefficients cannot meaningfully be compared.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] For example, for the three pairs (1, 1) (2, 3) (3, 2) Spearman's coefficient is 1/2, while Kendall's coefficient is 1/3.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The conventional dictum that "correlation does not imply causation" means that correlation cannot be used by itself to infer a causal relationship between the variables.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] This dictum should not be taken to mean that correlations cannot indicate the potential existence of causal relations.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] However, the causes underlying the correlation, if any, may be indirect and unknown, and high correlations also overlap with identity relations (tautologies), where no causal process exists (e.g., between two variables measuring the same construct).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Consequently, a correlation between two variables is not a sufficient condition to establish a causal relationship (in either direction).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] A correlation between age and height in children is fairly causally transparent, but a correlation between mood and health in people is less so.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Does improved mood lead to improved health, or does good health lead to good mood, or both?
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Or does some other factor underlie both?
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] In other words, a correlation can be taken as evidence for a possible causal relationship, but cannot indicate what the causal relationship, if any, might be.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The Pearson correlation coefficient indicates the strength of a *linear* relationship between two variables, but its value generally does not completely characterize their relationship.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] In particular, if the conditional mean of Y given X , denoted $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ , is not linear in X , the correlation coefficient will not fully determine the form of $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ .
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The adjacent image shows scatter plots of Anscombe's quartet, a set of four different pairs of variables created by Francis Anscombe.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The four y variables have the same mean (7.5), variance (4.12), correlation (0.816) and regression line ( ${\textstyle y=3+0.5x}$ ).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] However, as can be seen on the plots, the distribution of the variables is very different.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The first one (top left) seems to be distributed normally, and corresponds to what one would expect when considering two variables correlated and following the assumption of normality.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The second one (top right) is not distributed normally; while an obvious relationship between the two variables can be observed, it is not linear.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] In this case the Pearson correlation coefficient does not indicate that there is an exact functional relationship: only the extent to which that relationship can be approximated by a linear relationship.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] In the third case (bottom left), the linear relationship is perfect, except for one outlier which exerts enough influence to lower the correlation coefficient from 1 to 0.816.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Finally, the fourth example (bottom right) shows another example when one outlier is enough to produce a high correlation coefficient, even though the relationship between the two variables is not linear.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] These examples indicate that the correlation coefficient, as a summary statistic, cannot replace visual examination of the data.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The examples are sometimes said to demonstrate that the Pearson correlation assumes that the data follow a normal distribution, but this is only partially correct.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The Pearson correlation can be accurately calculated for any distribution that has a finite covariance matrix, which includes most distributions encountered in practice.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] However, the Pearson correlation coefficient (taken together with the sample mean and variance) is only a sufficient statistic if the data is drawn from a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] As a result, the Pearson correlation coefficient fully characterizes the relationship between variables if and only if the data are drawn from a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Similarly for two stochastic processes $\left\{X_{t}\right\}_{t\in {\mathcal {T}}}$ and $\left\{Y_{t}\right\}_{t\in {\mathcal {T}}}$ : If they are independent, then they are uncorrelated.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The opposite of this statement might not be true.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Even if two variables are uncorrelated, they might not be independent of each other.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The degree of dependence between variables X and Y does not depend on the scale on which the variables are expressed.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] That is, if we are analyzing the relationship between X and Y, most correlation measures are unaffected by transforming X to *a* + *bX* and Y to *c* + *dY*, where *a*, *b*, *c*, and *d* are constants (*b* and *d* being positive).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] This is true of some correlation statistics as well as their population analogues.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Some correlation statistics, such as the rank correlation coefficient, are also invariant to monotone transformations of the marginal distributions of X and/or Y.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Most correlation measures are sensitive to the manner in which X and Y are sampled.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Dependencies tend to be stronger if viewed over a wider range of values.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Several techniques have been developed that attempt to correct for range restriction in one or both variables, and are commonly used in meta-analysis; the most common are Thorndike's case II and case III equations.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Various correlation measures in use may be undefined for certain joint distributions of X and Y.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] For example, the Pearson correlation coefficient is defined in terms of moments, and hence will be undefined if the moments are undefined.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Measures of dependence based on quantiles are always defined.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Sample-based statistics intended to estimate population measures of dependence may or may not have desirable statistical properties such as being unbiased, or asymptotically consistent, based on the spatial structure of the population from which the data were sampled.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Sensitivity to the data distribution can be used to an advantage.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] For example, scaled correlation is designed to use the sensitivity to the range in order to pick out correlations between fast components of time series.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] By reducing the range of values in a controlled manner, the correlations on long time scale are filtered out and only the correlations on short time scales are revealed.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Thus the diagonal entries are all identically one.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] If the measures of correlation used are product-moment coefficients, the correlation matrix is the same as the covariance matrix of the standardized random variables $X_{i}/\sigma (X_{i})$ for $i=1,\dots ,n$ .
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] This applies both to the matrix of population correlations (in which case $\sigma$ is the population standard deviation), and to the matrix of sample correlations (in which case $\sigma$ denotes the sample standard deviation).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Consequently, each is necessarily a positive-semidefinite matrix.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Moreover, the correlation matrix is strictly positive definite if no variable can have all its values exactly generated as a linear function of the values of the others.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The correlation matrix is symmetric because the correlation between $X_{i}$ and $X_{j}$ is the same as the correlation between $X_{j}$ and $X_{i}$ .
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] A correlation matrix appears, for example, in one formula for the coefficient of multiple determination, a measure of goodness of fit in multiple regression.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] In statistical modelling, correlation matrices representing the relationships between variables are categorized into different correlation structures, which are distinguished by factors such as the number of parameters required to estimate them.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] For example, in an exchangeable correlation matrix, all pairs of variables are modeled as having the same correlation, so all non-diagonal elements of the matrix are equal to each other.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] On the other hand, an autoregressive matrix is often used when variables represent a time series, since correlations are likely to be greater when measurements are closer in time.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Other examples include independent, unstructured, M-dependent, and Toeplitz.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] In exploratory data analysis, the iconography of correlations consists in replacing a correlation matrix by a diagram where the "remarkable" correlations are represented by a solid line (positive correlation), or a dotted line (negative correlation).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] In some applications (e.g., building data models from only partially observed data) one wants to find the "nearest" correlation matrix to an "approximate" correlation matrix (e.g., a matrix which typically lacks positive semi-definiteness due to the way it has been computed).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] In 2002, Higham formalized the notion of nearness using the Frobenius norm and provided a method for computing the nearest correlation matrix using the Dykstra's projection algorithm.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] This sparked interest in the subject, with new theoretical (e.g., computing the nearest correlation matrix with factor structure) and numerical (e.g. usage of Newton's method for computing the nearest correlation matrix) results obtained in the subsequent years.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] where $\operatorname {\boldsymbol {\mathcal {E}}} (X)$ and $\operatorname {\boldsymbol {\mathcal {E}}} (Y)$ are the expected values of $\ X\$ and $\ Y\ ,$ respectively, and $\ \sigma _{X}\$ and $\ \sigma _{Y}\$ are the standard deviations of $\ X\$ and $\ Y\ ,$ respectively.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] where $\ F_{Hyp}\$ is the Gaussian hypergeometric function.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] This density is both a Bayesian posterior density and an exact optimal confidence distribution density.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The information given by a correlation coefficient is not enough to define the dependence structure between random variables.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The correlation coefficient completely defines the dependence structure only in very particular cases, for example when the distribution is a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] (See diagram above.) In the case of elliptical distributions it characterizes the (hyper-)ellipses of equal density; however, it does not completely characterize the dependence structure (for example, a multivariate t-distribution's degrees of freedom determine the level of tail dependence).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] For continuous variables, multiple alternative measures of dependence were introduced to address the deficiency of Pearson's correlation that it can be zero for dependent random variables (see and references therein for an overview).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] They all share the important property that a value of zero implies independence.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] This led some authors to recommend their routine usage, particularly of distance correlation.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Another alternative measure is the Randomized Dependence Coefficient.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The RDC is a computationally efficient, copula-based measure of dependence between multivariate random variables and is invariant with respect to non-linear scalings of random variables.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] One important disadvantage of the alternative, more general measures is that, when used to test whether two variables are associated, they tend to have lower power compared to Pearson's correlation when the data follow a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] This is an implication of the No free lunch theorem.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] To detect all kinds of relationships, these measures have to sacrifice power on other relationships, particularly for the important special case of a linear relationship with Gaussian marginals, for which Pearson's correlation is optimal.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Another problem concerns interpretation.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] While Pearson's correlation can be interpreted for all values, the alternative measures can generally only be interpreted meaningfully at the extremes.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] For two binary variables, the odds ratio measures their dependence, and takes a range of non-negative numbers, possibly infinity: ⁠ $[0,+\infty ]$ ⁠.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] Related statistics such as Yule's *Y* and Yule's *Q* normalize this to the correlation-like range ⁠ $[-1,1]$ ⁠.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/correlation] The odds ratio is generalized by the logistic model to model cases where the dependent variables are discrete and there may be one or more independent variables.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/event-log] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] In computer log management and intelligence, **log analysis** (or *system and network log analysis*) is an art and science seeking to make sense of computer-generated records (also called log or audit trail records).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] The process of creating such records is called data logging.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] Logs are emitted by network devices, operating systems, applications and all manner of intelligent or programmable devices.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] A stream of messages in time sequence often comprises a log.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] Logs may be directed to files and stored on disk or directed as a network stream to a log collector.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] Log messages must usually be interpreted concerning the internal state of its source (e.g., application) and announce security-relevant or operations-relevant events (e.g., a user login, or a systems error).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] Logs are often created by software developers to aid in the debugging of the operation of an application or understanding how users are interacting with a system, such as a search engine.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] The syntax and semantics of data within log messages are usually application or vendor-specific.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] The terminology may also vary; for example, the authentication of a user to an application may be described as a log in, a logon, a user connection or an authentication event.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] Hence, log analysis must interpret messages within the context of an application, vendor, system or configuration to make useful comparisons to messages from different log sources.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] Log message format or content may not always be fully documented.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] A task of the log analyst is to induce the system to emit the full range of messages to understand the complete domain from which the messages must be interpreted.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] A log analyst may map varying terminology from different log sources into a uniform, normalized terminology so that reports and statistics can be derived from a heterogeneous environment.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] For example, log messages from Windows, Unix, network firewalls, and databases may be aggregated into a "normalized" report for the auditor.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] Different systems may signal different message priorities with a different vocabulary, such as "error" and "warning" vs.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] Hence, log analysis practices exist on the continuum from text retrieval to reverse engineering of software.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] Log Analysis is often compared to other analytics tools such as application performance management (APM) and error monitoring.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] While much of their functionality is clear overlap, the difference is rooted in process.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] APM has an emphasis on performance and is utilized most in production.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/log-analysis] Error monitoring is driven by developers versus operations, and integrates into code in exception handling blocks.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] In computer science, a **rule-based system** is a computer system in which domain-specific knowledge is represented in the form of rules and general-purpose reasoning is used to solve problems in the domain.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] The differences and relationships between these two kinds of rule-based system has been a major source of misunderstanding and confusion.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] Both kinds of rule-based systems use either forward or backward chaining, in contrast with imperative programs, which execute commands listed sequentially.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] However, logic programming systems have a logical interpretation, whereas production systems do not.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] A classic example of a production rule-based system is the domain-specific expert system that uses rules to make deductions or choices.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] For example, an expert system might help a doctor choose the correct diagnosis based on a cluster of symptoms, or select tactical moves to play a game.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] Rule-based systems can be used to perform lexical analysis to compile or interpret computer programs, or in natural language processing.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] Rule-based programming attempts to derive execution instructions from a starting set of data and rules.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] This is a more indirect method than that employed by an imperative programming language, which lists execution steps sequentially.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] Whereas the matching phase of the inference engine has a logical interpretation, the conflict resolution and action phases do not.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] Instead, "their semantics is usually described as a series of applications of various state-changing operators, which often gets quite involved (depending on the choices made in deciding which ECA rules fire, when, and so forth), and they can hardly be regarded as declarative".
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] The logic programming family of computer systems includes the programming language Prolog, the database language Datalog and the knowledge representation and problem-solving language Answer Set Programming (ASP).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] In the simplest case of Horn clauses (or "definite" clauses), which are a subset of first-order logic, all of the A, B1, ..., Bn are atomic formulae.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] Although Horn clause logic programs are Turing complete, for many practical applications, it is useful to extend Horn clause programs by allowing negative conditions, implemented by negation as failure.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] Such extended logic programs have the knowledge representation capabilities of a non-monotonic logic.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] The most obvious difference between the two kinds of systems is that production rules are typically written in the forward direction, *if A then B*, and logic programming rules are typically written in the backward direction, *B if A*.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] In the case of logic programming rules, this difference is superficial and purely syntactic.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] It does not affect the semantics of the rules.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] Nor does it affect whether the rules are used to reason backwards, Prolog style, to reduce the goal *B* to the subgoals *A*, or whether they are used, Datalog style, to derive *B* from *A*.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] In the case of production rules, the forward direction of the syntax reflects the stimulus-response character of most production rules, with the stimulus *A* coming before the response *B*.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] Moreover, even in cases when the response is simply to draw a conclusion *B* from an assumption *A*, as in modus ponens, the match-resolve-act cycle is restricted to reasoning forwards from *A* to *B*.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] Reasoning backwards in a production system would require the use of an entirely different kind of inference engine.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] In his Introduction to Cognitive Science, Paul Thagard includes logic and rules as alternative approaches to modelling human thinking.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] He does not consider logic programs in general, but he considers Prolog to be, not a rule-based system, but "a programming language that uses logic representations and deductive techniques" (page 40).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] He argues that rules, which have the form *IF condition THEN action*, are "very similar" to logical conditionals, but they are simpler and have greater psychological plausibility (page 51).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] Among other differences between logic and rules, he argues that logic uses deduction, but rules use search (page 45) and can be used to reason either forward or backward (page 47).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] Sentences in logic "have to be interpreted as *universally true*", but rules can be *defaults*, which admit exceptions (page 44).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/rule-based-system] He does not observe that all of these features of rules apply to logic programming systems.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM tools can be implemented as software, hardware, or managed services.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems log security events and generate reports to meet regulatory frameworks such as the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) and the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] The integration of SIM and SEM within SIEM provides organizations with a centralized approach for monitoring security events and responding to threats in real-time.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] In recent years, SIEM has become increasingly incorporated into national cybersecurity initiatives.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] For instance, Executive Order 14028 signed in 2021 by U.S.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] President Joseph Biden mandates the use of SIEM technologies to improve incident detection and reporting in federal systems.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Compliance with these mandates is further reinforced by frameworks such as NIST SP 800-92, which outlines best practices for managing computer security logs.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Modern SIEM platforms are aggregating and normalizing data not only from various Information Technology (IT) sources, but from production and manufacturing Operational Technology (OT) environments as well.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Initially, system logging was primarily used for troubleshooting and debugging.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] However, as operating systems and networks have grown more complex, so has the generation of system logs.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] The monitoring of system logs has also become increasingly common due to the rise of sophisticated cyberattacks and the need for compliance with regulatory frameworks, which mandate logging security controls within risk management frameworks (RMF).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Starting in the late 1970s, working groups began establishing criteria for managing auditing and monitoring programs, laying the groundwork for modern cybersecurity practices, such as insider threat detection and incident response.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] A key publication during this period was NIST’s Special Publication 500-19.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] In 2005, the term "SIEM" (Security Information and Event Management) was introduced by Gartner analysts Mark Nicolett and Amrit Williams.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems provide a single interface for gathering security data from information systems and presenting it as actionable intelligence.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] With the implementation of RMFs globally, auditing and monitoring have become central to information assurance and security.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Cybersecurity professionals now rely on logging data to perform real-time security functions, driven by governance models that incorporate these processes into analytical tasks.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] As information assurance matured in the late 1990s and into the 2000s, the need to centralize system logs became apparent.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Centralized log management allows for easier oversight and coordination across networked systems.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] President Joseph Biden signed Executive Order 14028, "Improving the Nation's Cybersecurity," which established further logging requirements, including audit logging and endpoint protection, to enhance incident response capabilities.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] This order was a response to an increase in ransomware attacks targeting critical infrastructure.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] By reinforcing information assurance controls within RMFs, the order aimed to drive compliance and secure funding for cybersecurity initiatives.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Published in September 2006, the NIST SP 800-92 Guide to Computer Security Log Management serves as a key document within the NIST Risk Management Framework to guide what should be auditable.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] As indicated by the absence of the term "SIEM", the document was released before the widespread adoption of SIEM technologies.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Although the guide is not exhaustive due to rapid changes in technology since its publication, it remains relevant by anticipating industry growth.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] NIST is not the only source of guidance on regulatory mechanisms for auditing and monitoring, and many organizations are encouraged to adopt SIEM solutions rather than relying solely on host-based checks.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Public and private organizations frequently reference NIST documents in their security policies.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] NIST SP 800-53 AU-2 Event Monitoring is a key security control that supports system auditing and ensures continuous monitoring for information assurance and cybersecurity operations.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM solutions are typically employed as central tools for these efforts.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Federal systems categorized based on their impact on confidentiality, integrity, and availability (CIA) have five specific logging requirements (AU-2 a-e) that must be met.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] While logging every action is possible, it is generally not recommended due to the volume of logs and the need for actionable security data.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] AU-2 provides a foundation for organizations to build a logging strategy that aligns with other controls.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] NIST SP 800-53 SI-4 System Monitoring outlines the requirements for monitoring systems, including detecting unauthorized access and tracking anomalies, malware, and potential attacks.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] This security control specifies both the hardware and software requirements for detecting suspicious activities.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Similarly, NIST SP 800-53 RA-10 Threat Hunting, added in Revision 5, emphasizes proactive network defense by identifying threats that evade traditional controls.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM solutions play a critical role in aggregating security information for threat hunting teams.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Together, AU-2, SI-4, and RA-10 demonstrate how NIST controls integrate into a comprehensive security strategy.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] These controls, supported by SIEM solutions, help ensure continuous monitoring, risk assessments, and in-depth defense mechanisms across federal and private networks.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] In practice many products in this area will have a mix of these functions, so there will often be some overlap – and many commercial vendors also promote their own terminology.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Oftentimes commercial vendors provide different combinations of these functionalities which tend to improve SIEM overall.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Log management alone doesn't provide real-time insights on network security, SEM on its own won't provide complete data for deep threat analysis.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] When SEM and log management are combined, more information is available for SIEM to monitor.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] A key focus is to monitor and help manage user and service privileges, directory services and other system-configuration changes; as well as providing log auditing and review and incident response.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM architectures may vary by vendor; however, generally, essential components comprise the SIEM engine.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] A basic SIEM infrastructure is depicted in the image to the right.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Computer security researcher Chris Kubecka identified the following SIEM use cases, presented at the hacking conference 28C3 (Chaos Communication Congress).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Modern SIEM platforms support not only detection, but response too.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] The response can be manual or automated including AI based response.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems play a significant role in helping organizations meet regulatory compliance requirements by centralizing log collection, enabling real-time monitoring, and generating audit-ready reports.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Under the HIPAA Security Rule, covered entities must implement audit controls that record and examine activity in information systems containing electronic protected health information (ePHI).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would require covered entities to deploy technology capable of detecting and responding to security incidents within 24 hours, a capability commonly provided by SIEM platforms.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 10 mandates that organizations track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data, with SIEM systems commonly used to aggregate and analyze the required log data across distributed environments.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Similarly, the Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX) requires organizations to maintain audit trails for financial system access, and SIEM platforms provide the centralized logging and retention capabilities necessary to demonstrate compliance during audits.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems can have hundreds and thousands of correlation rules.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Some of these are simple, and some are more complex.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Once a correlation rule is triggered the system can take appropriate steps to mitigate a cyber attack.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Usually, this includes sending a notification to a user and then possibly limiting or even shutting down the system.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Brute force detection is relatively straightforward.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Brute forcing relates to continually trying to guess a variable.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] It most commonly refers to someone trying to constantly guess your password - either manually or with a tool.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] However, it can refer to trying to guess URLs or important file locations on your system.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] An automated brute force is easy to detect as someone trying to enter their password 60 times in a minute is impossible.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] When a user logs in to a system, generally speaking, it creates a timestamp of the event.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Alongside the time, the system may often record other useful information such as the device used, physical location, IP address, incorrect login attempts, etc.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] The more data is collected the more use can be gathered from it.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] For impossible travel, the system looks at the current and last login date/time and the difference between the recorded distances.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] If it deems it's not possible for this to happen, for example traveling hundreds of miles within a minute, then it will set off a warning.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Many employees and users are now using VPN services which may obscure physical location.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] This should be taken into consideration when setting up such a rule.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] The average user does not typically copy or move files on the system repeatedly.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Thus, any excessive file copying on a system could be attributed to an attacker wanting to cause harm to an organization.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Unfortunately, it's not as simple as stating someone has gained access to your network illegally and wants to steal confidential information.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] It could also be an employee looking to sell company information, or they could just want to take home some files for the weekend.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Monitoring network traffic against unusual patterns that includes any threats or attacks ranging from DDOS to network scans.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Note SIEM can monitor data flow in the network and to detect and prevent potential data exfiltration efforts.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] In general dedicated Data loss prevention (DLP) take care about data loss prevention.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] A DDoS (distributed denial of service) attack could cause significant damage to a company or organization.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] A DDoS attack can not only take a website offline, it can also make a system weaker.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] With suitable correlation rules in place, a SIEM should trigger an alert at the start of the attack so that the company can take the necessary precautionary measures to protect vital systems.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] File integrity and change monitoring (FIM) is the process of monitoring the files on your system.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Unexpected changes in your system files will trigger an alert as it's a likely indication of a cyber attack.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/security-information-and-event-management] Some examples of customized rules to alert on event conditions involve user authentication rules, attacks detected and infections detected.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Antivirus software was originally developed to detect and remove computer viruses, hence the name.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] However, with the proliferation of other malware, antivirus software started to protect against other computer threats.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Some products also include protection from malicious URLs, spam, and phishing.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The first known computer virus appeared in 1971 and was dubbed the "Creeper virus".
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] This computer virus infected Digital Equipment Corporation's (DEC) PDP-10 mainframe computers running the TENEX operating system.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The Creeper virus was eventually deleted by a program created by Ray Tomlinson and known as "The Reaper".
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Some people consider "The Reaper" the first antivirus software ever written – it may be the case, but the Reaper was actually a virus itself specifically designed to remove the Creeper virus.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The Creeper virus was followed by several other viruses.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The first known that appeared "in the wild" was "Elk Cloner", in 1981, which infected Apple II computers.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1983, the term *"computer virus"* was coined by Fred Cohen in one of the first ever published academic papers on computer viruses.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The first IBM PC compatible "in the wild" computer virus, and one of the first real widespread infections, was "Brain" in 1986.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] From then, the number of viruses has grown exponentially.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Most of the computer viruses written in the early and mid-1980s were limited to self-reproduction and had no specific damage routine built into the code.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] That changed when more and more programmers became acquainted with computer virus programming and created viruses that manipulated or even destroyed data on infected computers.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Before internet connectivity was widespread, computer viruses were typically spread by infected floppy disks.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Antivirus software came into use, but was updated relatively infrequently.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] During this time, virus checkers essentially had to check executable files and the boot sectors of floppy disks and hard disks.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] However, as internet usage became common, viruses began to spread online.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] There are competing claims for the innovator of the first antivirus product.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Possibly, the first publicly documented removal of an "in the wild" computer virus (the "Vienna virus") was performed by Bernd Fix in 1987.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1985, in United Kingdom, Jan Hruska and Peter Lammer founded the security firm Sophos and began producing their first antivirus and encryption products.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In the same period, in Hungary, VirusBuster was founded (and subsequently incorporated by Sophos).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1987, Andreas Lüning and Kai Figge, who founded G Data Software in 1985, released their first antivirus product for the Atari ST platform.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1987, the *Ultimate Virus Killer (UVK)* was also released.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] This was the de facto industry standard virus killer for the Atari ST and Atari Falcon, the last version of which (version 9.0) was released in April 2004.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1987, in the United States, John McAfee founded the McAfee company and, at the end of that year, he released the first version of VirusScan.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Also in 1987 (in Czechoslovakia), Peter Paško, Rudolf Hrubý, and Miroslav Trnka created the first version of NOD antivirus.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1987, Fred Cohen wrote that *there is no algorithm that can perfectly detect all possible computer viruses*.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Finally, at the end of 1987, the first two heuristic antivirus utilities were released: *Flushot Plus* by Ross Greenberg and *Anti4us* by Erwin Lanting.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] However, the kind of heuristic used by early AV engines was totally different from those used today.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The first product with a heuristic engine resembling modern ones was F-PROT in 1991.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Early heuristic engines were based on dividing the binary into different sections: data section, code section (in a legitimate binary, it usually starts always from the same location).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Indeed, the initial viruses re-organized the layout of the sections, or overrode the initial portion of a section in order to jump to the very end of the file where malicious code was located—only going back to resume execution of the original code.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] This was a very specific pattern, not used at the time by any legitimate software, which represented an elegant heuristic to catch suspicious code.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Other kinds of more advanced heuristics were later added, such as suspicious section names, incorrect header size, regular expressions, and partial pattern in-memory matching.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1988, the growth of antivirus companies continued.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In Germany, Tjark Auerbach founded Avira (*H+BEDV* at the time) and released the first version of *AntiVir* (named *"Luke Filewalker"* at the time).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In Spain, Carlos Jiménez released the first version of his antivirus (he founded Anyware Seguridad Informática, now part of McAfee, one year later).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In Bulgaria, Vesselin Bontchev released his first freeware antivirus program (he later joined FRISK Software).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Also Frans Veldman released the first version of ThunderByte Antivirus, also known as *TBAV* (he sold his company to Norman Safeground in 1998).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In Czechoslovakia, Pavel Baudiš and Eduard Kučera founded Avast Software (at the time *ALWIL Software*) and released their first version of avast! antivirus.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In June 1988, in South Korea, Ahn Cheol-Soo released its first antivirus software, called *V1* (he founded AhnLab later in 1995).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Finally, in autumn 1988, in the United Kingdom, Alan Solomon founded S&S International and created his *Dr.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Solomon's Anti-Virus Toolkit* (although he launched it commercially only in 1991 – in 1998 Solomon's company was acquired by McAfee, then known as Network Associates Inc.).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Also in 1988, a mailing list named VIRUS-L was started on the BITNET/EARN network where new viruses and the possibilities of detecting and eliminating viruses were discussed.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Some members of this mailing list were: Alan Solomon, Eugene Kaspersky (Kaspersky Lab), Friðrik Skúlason (FRISK Software), John McAfee (McAfee), Luis Corrons (Panda Security), Mikko Hyppönen (F-Secure), Péter Szőr, Tjark Auerbach (Avira) and Vesselin Bontchev (FRISK Software).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1989, in Iceland, Friðrik Skúlason created the first version of F-PROT Anti-Virus (he founded FRISK Software only in 1993).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Meanwhile, in the United States, Symantec (founded by Gary Hendrix in 1982) launched its first *Symantec antivirus for Macintosh* (SAM).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] SAM 2.0, released March 1990, incorporated technology allowing users to easily update SAM to intercept and eliminate new viruses, including many that didn't exist at the time of the program's release.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1990, in Spain, Mikel Urizarbarrena founded Panda Security (*Panda Software* at the time).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In Hungary, the security researcher Péter Szőr released the first version of *Pasteur* antivirus.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1990, the Computer Antivirus Research Organization (CARO) was founded.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1991, CARO released the *"Virus Naming Scheme"*, originally written by Friðrik Skúlason and Vesselin Bontchev.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Although this naming scheme is now outdated, it remains the only existing standard that most computer security companies and researchers ever attempted to adopt.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] CARO members includes: Alan Solomon, Costin Raiu, Dmitry Gryaznov, Eugene Kaspersky, Friðrik Skúlason, Igor Muttik, Mikko Hyppönen, Morton Swimmer, Nick FitzGerald, Padgett Peterson, Peter Ferrie, Righard Zwienenberg and Vesselin Bontchev.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1991, in the United States, Symantec released the first version of Norton AntiVirus.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] On the other hand, in Finland, F-Secure (founded in 1988 by Petri Allas and Risto Siilasmaa – with the name of Data Fellows) released the first version of their antivirus product.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] F-Secure claims to be the first antivirus firm to establish a presence on the World Wide Web.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1991, the European Institute for Computer Antivirus Research (EICAR) was founded to further antivirus research and improve development of antivirus software.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1992, in Russia, Igor Danilov released the first version of *SpiderWeb*, which later became Dr.Web.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1994, AV-TEST reported that there were 28,613 unique malware samples (based on MD5) in their database.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1996, in Romania, Bitdefender was founded and released the first version of *Anti-Virus eXpert* (AVX).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1997, in Russia, Eugene Kaspersky and Natalya Kaspersky co-founded security firm Kaspersky Lab.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1996, there was also the first "in the wild" Linux virus, known as *"Staog"*.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 1999, AV-TEST reported that there were 98,428 unique malware samples (based on MD5) in their database.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 2000, Rainer Link and Howard Fuhs started the first open source antivirus engine, called *OpenAntivirus Project*.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 2001, Tomasz Kojm released the first version of ClamAV, the first ever open source antivirus engine to be commercialised.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 2007, ClamAV was bought by Sourcefire, which in turn was acquired by Cisco Systems in 2013.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 2002, in United Kingdom, Morten Lund and Theis Søndergaard co-founded the antivirus firm BullGuard.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 2005, AV-TEST reported that there were 333,425 unique malware samples (based on MD5) in their database.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 2007, AV-TEST reported a number of 5,490,960 new unique malware samples (based on MD5) only for that year.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 2012 and 2013, antivirus firms reported a new malware samples range from 300,000 to over 500,000 per day.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 2005, F-Secure was the first security firm that developed an Anti-Rootkit technology, called *BlackLight*.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Because most users are usually connected to the Internet on a continual basis, Jon Oberheide first proposed a Cloud-based antivirus design in 2008.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In February 2008 McAfee Labs added the industry-first cloud-based anti-malware functionality to VirusScan under the name Artemis.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] It was tested by AV-Comparatives in February 2008 and officially unveiled in August 2008 in McAfee VirusScan.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Cloud AV created problems for comparative testing of security software – part of the AV definitions was out of testers control (on constantly updated AV company servers) thus making results non-repeatable.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] As a result, Anti-Malware Testing Standards Organisation (AMTSO) started working on method of testing cloud products which was adopted on May 7, 2009.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 2011, AVG introduced a similar cloud service, called Protective Cloud Technology.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Following the 2013 release of the APT 1 report from Mandiant, the industry has seen a shift towards signature-less approaches to the problem capable of detecting and mitigating zero-day attacks.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Numerous approaches to address these new forms of threats have appeared, including behavioral detection, artificial intelligence, machine learning, and cloud-based file detection.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] According to Gartner, it is expected the rise of new entrants, such Carbon Black, Cylance and Crowdstrike will force end point protection incumbents into a new phase of innovation and acquisition.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] One method from Bromium involves micro-virtualization to protect desktops from malicious code execution initiated by the end user.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Another approach from SentinelOne and Carbon Black focuses on behavioral detection by building a full context around every process execution path in real time, while Cylance leverages an artificial intelligence model based on machine learning.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Increasingly, these signature-less approaches have been defined by the media and analyst firms as "next-generation" antivirus and are seeing rapid market adoption as certified antivirus replacement technologies by firms such as Coalfire and DirectDefense.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In response, traditional antivirus vendors such as Trend Micro, Symantec and Sophos have responded by incorporating "next-gen" offerings into their portfolios as analyst firms such as Forrester and Gartner have called traditional signature-based antivirus "ineffective" and "outdated".
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] As of Windows 8, Windows includes its own free antivirus protection under the Windows Defender brand.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Despite bad detection scores in its early days, AV-Test now certifies Defender as one of its top products.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] While it isn't publicly known how the inclusion of antivirus software in Windows affected antivirus sales, Google search traffic for antivirus has declined significantly since 2010.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Since 2016, there has been a notable amount of consolidation in the industry.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Avast purchased AVG in 2016 for $1.3 billion.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Avira was acquired by Norton owner Gen Digital (then NortonLifeLock) in 2020 for $360 million.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 2021, the Avira division of Gen Digital acquired BullGuard.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The BullGuard brand was discontinued in 2022 and its customers were migrated to Norton.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 2022, Gen Digital acquired Avast, effectively consolidating four major antivirus brands under one owner.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In September 2024, following the US Commerce Department's ban on Kaspersky, Pango Group acquired its customers (about 1 million).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The customers received continued services with no action required on their part.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Then, in December 2024, Pango Group merged with Total Security, the provider of Total AV antivirus.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The combined entity, now called Point Wild, has an enterprise value of $1.7 billion.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] As of 2024, more than half of Americans use built-in antivirus protection for their devices like Microsoft Defender or XProtect from Apple.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] However, about 121 million adults still use third-party antivirus software.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Half of these adults use paid products, and about 50% of third-party software users - the owners of personal computers and Windows operating systems.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Antivirus programs on mobile devices are used by 17% of adults.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The 2025 antivirus market report confirms that most third-party antivirus users are on desktop devices, primarily aged between 35 and 45.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In contrast, younger users (18–25) tend to rely on ad blockers instead.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In the U.S., on average, 75–85% of people use antivirus software or some other form of protection on at least one device.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Antivirus software for computers and mobile devices is predominantly used by residents of large cities.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Mobile device users more often rely on password managers rather than antivirus software for digital security.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Moreover, the majority of password‑manager users live in medium‑sized and small towns.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Cohen demonstrated that the algorithm which would be able to detect all possible viruses can't possibly exist (like the algorithm which determines whether or not the given program halts).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] However, using different layers of defense, a good detection rate may be achieved.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Traditional antivirus software relies heavily upon signatures to identify malware.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Substantially, when a malware sample arrives in the hands of an antivirus firm, it is analysed by malware researchers or by dynamic analysis systems.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Then, once it is determined to be a malware, a proper signature of the file is extracted and added to the signatures database of the antivirus software.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Many viruses start as a single infection and through either mutation or refinements by other attackers, can grow into dozens of slightly different strains, called variants.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Generic detection refers to the detection and removal of multiple threats using a single virus definition.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] For example, the Vundo trojan has several family members, depending on the antivirus vendor's classification.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Symantec classifies members of the Vundo family into two distinct categories, *Trojan.Vundo* and *Trojan.Vundo.B*.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] While it may be advantageous to identify a specific virus, it can be quicker to detect a virus family through a generic signature or through an inexact match to an existing signature.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Virus researchers find common areas that all viruses in a family share uniquely and can thus create a single generic signature.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] These signatures often contain non-contiguous code, using wildcard characters where differences lie.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] These wildcards allow the scanner to detect viruses even if they are padded with extra, meaningless code.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] A detection that uses this method is said to be "heuristic detection".
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Anti-virus software can attempt to scan for rootkits.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] A rootkit is a type of malware designed to gain administrative-level control over a computer system without being detected.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Rootkits can change how the operating system functions and in some cases can tamper with the anti-virus program and render it ineffective.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Rootkits are also difficult to remove, in some cases requiring a complete re-installation of the operating system.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Real-time protection, on-access scanning, background guard, resident shield, autoprotect, and other synonyms refer to the automatic protection provided by most antivirus, anti-spyware, and other anti-malware programs.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] This monitors computer systems for suspicious activity such as computer viruses, spyware, adware, and other malicious objects.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Real-time protection detects threats in opened files and scans apps in real-time as they are installed on the device.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] When inserting a CD, opening an email, or browsing the web, or when a file already on the computer is opened or executed.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Machine learning has emerged as a core detection method in modern antivirus software, using algorithms trained on large datasets to classify software as malicious or benign.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] ML-based approaches are diverse, but detectors typically extract features from files, such as API call sequences, byte n-grams, opcode distributions, behavioral characteristics, or even raw bytes, and train classifiers to identify malware based on learned patterns from this data.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] ML-based detection can be highly effective, but still faces significant challenges.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Concept drift occurs as malware continuously evolves, causing trained models to degrade in accuracy over time without regular retraining on fresh samples.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Research has demonstrated that even simple obfuscation techniques can create adversarial variants that bypass ML-based detectors while preserving malicious functionality.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Additionally, the highly imbalanced nature of real-world data, where benign files vastly outnumber malicious ones, makes acquiring training data difficult and requires careful tuning to avoid unacceptable false positive rates.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Some commercial antivirus software end-user license agreements include a clause that the subscription will be automatically renewed, and the purchaser's credit card automatically billed, at the renewal time without explicit approval.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] For example, McAfee requires users to unsubscribe at least 60 days before the expiration of the present subscription, while Bitdefender sends notifications to unsubscribe 30 days before the renewal.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Norton AntiVirus also renews subscriptions automatically by default.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Some apparent antivirus programs are actually malware masquerading as legitimate software, such as WinFixer, MS Antivirus, and Mac Defender.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] A "false positive" or "false alarm" is when antivirus software identifies a non-malicious file as malware.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] When this happens, it can cause serious problems.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] For example, if an antivirus program is configured to immediately delete or quarantine infected files, as is common on Microsoft Windows antivirus applications, a false positive in an essential file can render the Windows operating system or some applications unusable.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Recovering from such damage to critical software infrastructure incurs technical support costs and businesses can be forced to close whilst remedial action is undertaken.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Running (the real-time protection of) multiple antivirus programs concurrently can degrade performance and create conflicts.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] However, using a concept called multiscanning, several companies (including G Data Software and Microsoft) have created applications which can run multiple engines concurrently.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] It is sometimes necessary to temporarily disable virus protection when installing major updates such as Windows Service Packs or updating graphics card drivers.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Active antivirus protection may partially or completely prevent the installation of a major update.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Anti-virus software can cause problems during the installation of an operating system upgrade, e.g. when upgrading to a newer version of Windows "in place"—without erasing the previous version of Windows.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Microsoft recommends that anti-virus software be disabled to avoid conflicts with the upgrade installation process.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Active anti-virus software can also interfere with a firmware update process.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The functionality of a few computer programs can be hampered by active anti-virus software.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] For example, TrueCrypt, a disk encryption program, states on its troubleshooting page that anti-virus programs can conflict with TrueCrypt and cause it to malfunction or operate very slowly.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Anti-virus software can impair the performance and stability of games running in the Steam platform.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Support issues also exist around antivirus application interoperability with common solutions like SSL VPN remote access and network access control products.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] These technology solutions often have policy assessment applications that require an up-to-date antivirus to be installed and running.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] If the antivirus application is not recognized by the policy assessment, whether because the antivirus application has been updated or because it is not part of the policy assessment library, the user will be unable to connect.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Studies in December 2007 showed that the effectiveness of antivirus software had decreased in the previous year, particularly against unknown or zero day attacks.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The computer magazine *c't* found that detection rates for these threats had dropped from 40 to 50% in 2006 to 20–30% in 2007.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] At that time, the only exception was the NOD32 antivirus, which managed a detection rate of 68%.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] According to the *ZeuS tracker* website the average detection rate for all variants of the ZeuS trojan is as low as 40%.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The problem is magnified by the changing intent of virus authors.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Some years ago it was obvious when a virus infection was present.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] At the time, viruses were written by amateurs and exhibited destructive behavior or pop-ups.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Modern viruses are often written by professionals, financed by criminal organizations.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 2008, Eva Chen, CEO of Trend Micro, stated that the anti-virus industry has over-hyped how effective its products are—and so has been misleading customers—for years.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Independent testing on all the major virus scanners consistently shows that none provides 100% virus detection.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The best ones provided as high as 99.9% detection for simulated real-world situations, while the lowest provided 91.1% in tests conducted in August 2013.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Many virus scanners produce false positive results as well, identifying benign files as malware.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Although methods may differ, some notable independent quality testing agencies include AV-Comparatives, ICSA Labs, SE Labs, West Coast Labs, *Virus Bulletin*, AV-TEST and other members of the Anti-Malware Testing Standards Organization.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Anti-virus programs are not always effective against new viruses, even those that use non-signature-based methods that should detect new viruses.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The reason for this is that the virus designers test their new viruses on the major anti-virus applications to make sure that they are not detected before releasing them into the wild.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Some new viruses, particularly ransomware, use polymorphic code to avoid detection by virus scanners.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] A proof of concept virus has used the Graphics Processing Unit (GPU) to avoid detection from anti-virus software.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The potential success of this involves bypassing the CPU in order to make it much harder for security researchers to analyse the inner workings of such malware.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Detecting rootkits is a major challenge for anti-virus programs.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Rootkits have full administrative access to the computer and are invisible to users and hidden from the list of running processes in the task manager.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Rootkits can modify the inner workings of the operating system and tamper with antivirus programs.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] If a file has been infected by a computer virus, anti-virus software will attempt to remove the virus code from the file during disinfection, but it is not always able to restore the file to its undamaged state.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In such circumstances, damaged files can only be restored from existing backups or shadow copies (this is also true for ransomware); installed software that is damaged requires re-installation (however, see System File Checker).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Any writeable firmware in the computer can be infected by malicious code.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] This is a major concern, as an infected BIOS could require the actual BIOS chip to be replaced to ensure the malicious code is completely removed.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Anti-virus software is not effective at protecting firmware and the motherboard BIOS from infection.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] In 2014, security researchers discovered that USB devices contain writeable firmware which can be modified with malicious code (dubbed "BadUSB"), which anti-virus software cannot detect or prevent.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The malicious code can run undetected on the computer and could even infect the operating system prior to it booting up.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Antivirus software has some drawbacks, first of which that it can impact a computer's performance.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Furthermore, inexperienced users can be lulled into a false sense of security when using the computer, considering their computers to be invulnerable, and may have problems understanding the prompts and decisions that antivirus software presents them with.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] An incorrect decision may lead to a security breach.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] If the antivirus software employs heuristic detection, it must be fine-tuned to minimize misidentifying harmless software as malicious (false positive).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Antivirus software itself usually runs at the highly trusted kernel level of the operating system to allow it access to all the potential malicious process and files, creating a potential avenue of attack.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] The US National Security Agency (NSA) and the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ) intelligence agencies, respectively, have been exploiting anti-virus software to spy on users.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Anti-virus software has highly privileged and trusted access to the underlying operating system, which makes it a much more appealing target for remote attacks.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Additionally anti-virus software is "years behind security-conscious client-side applications like browsers or document readers.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] It means that Acrobat Reader, Microsoft Word or Google Chrome are harder to exploit than 90 percent of the anti-virus products out there", according to Joxean Koret, a researcher with Coseinc, a Singapore-based information security consultancy.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Antivirus software running on individual computers is the most common method employed of guarding against malware, but it is not the only solution.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Other solutions can also be employed by users, including Unified Threat Management (UTM), hardware and network firewalls, Cloud-based antivirus, online scanners, and Content Disarm & Reconstruction (CDR).
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Network firewalls prevent unknown programs and processes from accessing the system.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] However, they are not antivirus systems and make no attempt to identify or remove anything.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] They may protect against infection from outside the protected computer or network, and limit the activity of any malicious software which is present by blocking incoming or outgoing requests on certain TCP/IP ports.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] A firewall is designed to deal with broader system threats that come from network connections into the system and is not an alternative to a virus protection system.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Cloud antivirus is a technology that uses lightweight agent software on the protected computer, while offloading the majority of data analysis to the provider's infrastructure.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] One approach to implementing cloud antivirus involves scanning suspicious files using multiple antivirus engines.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] This approach was proposed by an early implementation of the cloud antivirus concept called CloudAV.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] CloudAV was designed to send programs or documents to a network cloud where multiple antivirus and behavioral detection programs are used simultaneously in order to improve detection rates.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Parallel scanning of files using potentially incompatible antivirus scanners is achieved by spawning a virtual machine per detection engine and therefore eliminating any possible issues.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] CloudAV can also perform "retrospective detection", whereby the cloud detection engine rescans all files in its file access history when a new threat is identified thus improving new threat detection speed.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Finally, CloudAV is a solution for effective virus scanning on devices that lack the computing power to perform the scans themselves.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Some examples of cloud anti-virus products are Panda Cloud Antivirus and Immunet.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Comodo Group has also produced cloud-based anti-virus.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Some antivirus vendors maintain websites with free online scanning capability of the entire computer, critical areas only, local disks, folders or files.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Periodic online scanning is a good idea for those that run antivirus applications on their computers because those applications are frequently slow to catch threats.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] One of the first things that malicious software does in an attack is disable any existing antivirus software and sometimes the only way to know of an attack is by turning to an online resource that is not installed on the infected computer.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Content Disarm & Reconstruction (CDR) technology protects a network from malware by removing components from inbound files which do not rigorously conform with the standards of that file type.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] It does so by rebuilding the original files without any illegitimate components present.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Part of the CDR process may also involve flattening and converting the reconstructed files to Portable Document Format (PDF) for maximum safety.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] CDR malware removal does not attempt to identify malware behavior before taking action; rather, it employs a zero-trust approach against files entering a network perimeter.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] This can make it an effective solution for protecting networks against zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Virus removal tools are available to help remove stubborn infections or a certain type of infection.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Examples include *Windows Malicious Software Removal Tool*, *Kaspersky Virus Removal Tool*, and *Sophos Scan & Clean*.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] It is also worth noting that sometimes antivirus software can produce a false-positive result, indicating an infection where there is none.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] A rescue disk that is bootable, such as a CD or USB storage device, can be used to run antivirus software outside of the installed operating system in order to remove infections while they are dormant.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] A bootable rescue disk can be useful when, for example, the installed operating system is no longer bootable or has malware that is resisting all attempts to be removed by the installed antivirus software.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] Examples of software that can be used on a bootable rescue disk include the *Kaspersky Rescue Disk*, *Trend Micro Rescue Disk*, and *Comodo Rescue Disk*.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] According to an FBI survey, major businesses lose $12 million annually dealing with virus incidents.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] A survey by Symantec in 2009 found that a third of small to medium-sized business did not use antivirus protection at that time, whereas more than 80% of home users had some kind of antivirus installed.
[src:sigma-detection-rules/signature-based-detection] According to a sociological survey conducted by G Data Software in 2010 49% of women did not use any antivirus program at all.
